## Why This Is Asked
Tests multi-tenant inference design, signature layout, per-tenant batching, and observability in Kubernetes TF Serving.

## Key Concepts
- Shared backbone with per-tenant heads via multiple signatures
- Per-tenant batching configs and queues
- Isolation: separate queues, metrics, and cache boundaries
- Observability: per-tenant SLAs, latency percentiles, and QPS

## Code Example
```python
import tensorflow as tf
class Backbone(tf.keras.Model):
  def __init__(self):
    super().__init__(); self.layer = tf.keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu')
  def call(self, x): return self.layer(x)
class HeadA(tf.keras.Model):
  def __init__(self): super().__init__(); self.out = tf.keras.layers.Dense(2)
  def call(self, z): return self.out(z)
class HeadB(tf.keras.Model):
  def __init__(self): super().__init__(); self.out = tf.keras.layers.Dense(3)
  def call(self, z): return self.out(z)
class MultiTenant(tf.keras.Model):
  def __init__(self):
    super().__init__(); self.backbone = Backbone(); self.headA = HeadA(); self.headB = HeadB()
  @tf.function(input_signature=[tf.TensorSpec([None, 16], tf.float32)])
  def serve_headA(self, x):
    z = self.backbone(x)
    return {"logits": self.headA(z)}
  @tf.function(input_signature=[tf.TensorSpec([None, 16], tf.float32)])
  def serve_headB(self, x):
    z = self.backbone(x)
    return {"logits": self.headB(z)}
model = MultiTenant()
tf.saved_model.save(model, "saved/mt_serving", signatures={
  "serve_headA": model.serve_headA.get_concrete_function(),
  "serve_headB": model.serve_headB.get_concrete_function()
})
```

