## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to design multi-input serving with optional inputs and multiple signatures in TF SavedModel.

## Key Concepts
- tf.saved_model, serving signatures, tf.keras.Input, tf.function, concrete functions, multiple signatures, default inputs.

## Code Example
```javascript
import tensorflow as tf

# Python-like example shown here for TF SavedModel export

def build_model():
    image = tf.keras.Input(shape=(224,224,3), name='image')
    feats = tf.keras.Input(shape=(10,), name='features')
    x = tf.keras.layers.Flatten()(image)
    x = tf.keras.layers.Concatenate()([x, feats])
    out = tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)
    return tf.keras.Model(inputs=[image, feats], outputs=out)

model = build_model()

@tf.function(input_signature=[tf.TensorSpec([None,224,224,3], tf.float32, name='image'),
                              tf.TensorSpec([None,10], tf.float32, name='features')])
def serve_full(image, features):
    return {'outputs': model([image, features])}

@tf.function(input_signature=[tf.TensorSpec([None,224,224,3], tf.float32, name='image')])
def serve_image_only(image):
    default_features = tf.zeros([tf.shape(image)[0], 10], dtype=tf.float32)
    return {'outputs': model([image, default_features])}

tf.saved_model.save(model, 'saved_model', signatures={
  'serving_default': serve_full.get_concrete_function(),
  'image_only': serve_image_only.get_concrete_function(),
})
```

